Here's an example Java function to output all matches of a given regex inside a string:

```
import java.util.regex.Matcher;
import java.util.regex.Pattern;

public class RegexMatcher {
  public static void findMatches(String input, String regex) {
    Pattern pattern = Pattern.compile(regex);
    Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(input);

    while (matcher.find()) {
      System.out.println("Match found: " + matcher.group());
    }
  }

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    String input = "This is an example string with an address https://www.example.com.";
    String regex = "example\\.com";
    findMatches(input, regex);
  }
}
```

This code defines a function called `findMatches` that takes the input string and regex as parameters. It then compiles the regex into a `Pattern` object, creates a `Matcher` object using the input string, and loops through all the matches using `matcher.find()`. For each match, it prints out the matched string using `matcher.group()`. Finally, the `main` method calls `findMatches` with the example input and regex. 

In this case, the output of running this code would be:

```
Match found: example.com
```

An API endpoint for retrieving customer orders by the customer ID can be created using various programming languages and frameworks. Below is an example using Node.js and Express.js.

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const router = express.Router();

// Assuming that we have a function that retrieves the customer orders from the database
const getCustomerOrders = require('../database/getCustomerOrders');

// Endpoint URL: /orders/customer/:customerId
router.get('/customer/:customerId', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const customerId = req.params.customerId;
    const customerOrders = await getCustomerOrders(customerId);
    res.status(200).json(customerOrders);
  } catch (error) {
    res.status(500).json({ message: 'Error retrieving customer orders' });
  }
});

module.exports = router;
```

This endpoint can be accessed using the URL: `/orders/customer/:customerId` where `:customerId` is the ID of the customer whose orders we want to retrieve. The `getCustomerOrders` function retrieves the customers' orders from the database using the provided customer ID and returns them as JSON data. Any errors that occur during the process are handled by returning a `500` HTTP status code with an error message.

